- Well,
I like timeless performances,

16:02.570 --> 16:05.970
and, um, yeah,
I'm mostly inspired by the past

16:05.970 --> 16:08.470
because I think there have
been lots of ideas

16:08.470 --> 16:10.669
that have been discovered
in the past,

16:10.669 --> 16:13.330
but they are some sort of--
of forgotten.

16:13.330 --> 16:16.169
And nowadays, the world
is turning faster and faster,

16:16.169 --> 16:19.100
so I like to rely
on those old things,

16:19.100 --> 16:22.000
and, um, yeah, dress that way,
behave that way,

16:22.000 --> 16:24.529
and live those old ideas.

16:24.529 --> 16:26.470
Yeah, you won't find
a smartphone on me anywhere.

16:26.470 --> 16:27.870
- Oh, good.

16:27.870 --> 16:29.700
All right, well let's see
if your performance

16:29.700 --> 16:31.000
fooled Penn and Teller.

16:31.000 --> 16:33.129
- [chuckles]
- Penn, Teller.

16:33.129 --> 16:34.129
- Hey.
- Oh, boy.

16:34.129 --> 16:36.600
Man, Patrick, it's so good.

16:36.600 --> 16:38.470
You know, we talk,
on this show--

16:38.470 --> 16:39.870
it's "Penn & Teller: Fool Us,"

16:39.870 --> 16:43.129
and that means that we're
always talking about methods.

16:43.129 --> 16:44.330
- Mm-hmm.
- It's always,

16:44.330 --> 16:45.529
"How do they do it?
How do they do it?

16:45.529 --> 16:46.870
How do they do it?"

16:46.870 --> 16:48.629
But it's rare
that someone comes along

16:48.629 --> 16:50.669
and we get to say,
"What did he do?"

16:50.669 --> 16:54.500
And you did something here
that is a new effect.

16:54.500 --> 16:56.070
It's not a new way
of doing something

16:56.070 --> 16:58.230
a lot of people have done,
it's a new idea.

16:58.230 --> 16:59.899
Now, this is
a mathematical thing.

16:59.899 --> 17:02.399
We've all seen the puzzle--
two-dimensional.

17:02.399 --> 17:03.730
We know how that moves around.

17:03.730 --> 17:05.029
That's not what you're doing.

17:05.029 --> 17:06.700
You're doing something
that takes from that

17:06.700 --> 17:08.868
and--and--and grows tremendously.

17:08.868 --> 17:10.368
What's so wonderful
about this--

17:10.368 --> 17:11.529
boy, I like this!

17:11.529 --> 17:13.900
I liked it
because it's so sweet,

17:13.900 --> 17:16.769
it's so, um,
it's--it's so tactile.

17:16.769 --> 17:18.569
Doing it three-dimensional
was wonderful.

17:18.569 --> 17:22.000
And also, you use
the mathematical principles

17:22.000 --> 17:24.098
that are used in this
in order to conceal

17:24.098 --> 17:26.769
when you did
the, uh, dirty work--

17:26.769 --> 17:28.069
uh, dirty work earlier.

17:28.069 --> 17:30.099
- Mm-hmm.
- It's a displacement in time,

17:30.099 --> 17:31.630
and I want to give you
a chance here...

17:31.630 --> 17:33.200
[coughs]
'Cause we're going one

17:33.200 --> 17:34.500
of two ways...
- Uh-huh.

17:34.500 --> 17:36.200
- Okay?
Now we gotta choose one,

17:36.200 --> 17:38.700
we can't just take more
and more bites of this apple.

17:38.700 --> 17:41.799
So I'm gonna tell you,
we do not think...

17:41.799 --> 17:43.470
that you snuck one
of the pieces out.

17:43.470 --> 17:44.769
We don't think you did that.

17:44.769 --> 17:46.869
And if you snuck one
of the pieces out,

17:46.869 --> 17:49.130
and we didn't see ya,
you can tell us right now

17:49.130 --> 17:50.430
that you've won.

17:50.430 --> 17:52.470
- No, not that way.
- But you didn't.

17:52.470 --> 17:53.930
You're too good for that.

17:53.930 --> 17:56.630
Uh, what we loved about this
is the whole effect

17:56.630 --> 18:00.369
and how you compress
all of life into one piece.

18:00.369 --> 18:03.029
This whole thing that you're
talking about doing--

18:03.029 --> 18:05.269
which is, "I'm gonna tell you
the story of life"--

18:05.269 --> 18:07.799
you really kind of did,
and we just loved it.

18:07.799 --> 18:10.799
And I gotta tell ya,
whether you fooled us or not,

18:10.799 --> 18:12.470
that is a fabulous effect.

18:12.470 --> 18:14.569
And we spend a lot
of our time thinking,

18:14.569 --> 18:16.170
"What tricks can we do?"

18:16.170 --> 18:18.299
It may be harder
than how you do 'em,

18:18.299 --> 18:19.630
and you've done
that part of it,

18:19.630 --> 18:22.099
but I don't think
you fooled us.

18:22.099 --> 18:24.099
- So, did they figure it out?

18:24.099 --> 18:25.700
- Oh, that sounded perfectly.

18:25.700 --> 18:28.230
I'm fine with that,
and I think, um, we both--

18:28.230 --> 18:30.799
we're all happy.
[laughter]

18:30.799 --> 18:32.529
- All right!
- Such a great act.

18:32.529 --> 18:34.670
- Patrick Folkerts!

18:34.670 --> 18:37.000
- Thank you, cheers.
- Thank you.

18:37.000 --> 18:38.869
- So good, man.

18:38.869 --> 18:41.700
[cheering and applause]

18:42.929 --> 18:46.199
- Don't blink, because we have
more magic tricks on the way.

18:46.199 --> 18:47.729
Stick around!

18:47.729 --> 18:49.100
[cheering and applause]

18:49.100 --> 18:52.100
<i>[jazz music]</i>

18:55.419 --> 18:57.479
<i>[jazz music]</i>

18:57.479 --> 19:00.280
[applause]

19:00.280 --> 19:02.179
- Welcome back to "Fool Us"!

19:02.179 --> 19:04.479
We've seen one fooler
so far tonight.

19:04.479 --> 19:07.650
Let's go for two
as we meet our next magician:

19:09.679 --> 19:11.719
- I've always been fascinated
by mirrors.

19:11.719 --> 19:13.249
<i>I used to stare into them.</i>

19:13.249 --> 19:15.080
<i>"Is it an alternate universe?"</i>

19:15.080 --> 19:17.320
<i>I have always wanted
to get inside and find out.</i>

19:17.320 --> 19:19.380
<i>[mysterious music]</i>

19:19.380 --> 19:20.749
<i>"But what if
I get trapped inside?</i>

19:20.749 --> 19:22.679
<i>I can never come home."</i>

19:22.679 --> 19:25.419
<i>When I was a kid, I always had
to figure out how things work.</i>

19:25.419 --> 19:26.719
<i>I would go to the library</i>

19:26.719 --> 19:28.949
<i>and learn about
all kinds of subjects.</i>

19:28.949 --> 19:31.320
<i>Magic was the perfect medium
for me.</i>

19:31.320 --> 19:32.620
<i>You take everything
you've ever learned,</i>

19:32.620 --> 19:33.949
<i>all the books you've read,</i>

19:33.949 --> 19:35.449
<i>all your
childhood experiences,</i>

19:35.449 --> 19:37.050
<i>and you use all those tools</i>

19:37.050 --> 19:40.080
<i>to make an illusion
into reality.</i>

19:40.080 --> 19:42.650
<i>Outside the mirror
is the real world.</i>

19:42.650 --> 19:45.519
<i>If I can get out, I can take
what I've learned with me</i>

19:45.519 --> 19:47.050
<i>and put together a trick</i>

19:47.050 --> 19:49.880
<i>that will blow
Penn and Teller away.</i>

19:49.880 --> 19:54.019
[cheering and applause]

19:54.019 --> 19:57.580
- Please welcome the magic
of Migz!

19:57.580 --> 20:01.580
[cheering and applause]

20:01.580 --> 20:03.580
- Now, magic has taken me
years and years

20:03.580 --> 20:05.019
to learn how to do.

20:05.019 --> 20:07.120
Many lonely years...
[giggle]

20:07.120 --> 20:08.479
in front of a mirror.

20:08.479 --> 20:10.320
Well, you'd be surprised
how much time magicians spend

20:10.320 --> 20:11.949
in front of mirrors,
and some of them...

20:11.949 --> 20:14.919
even practice.
[laughter]

20:14.919 --> 20:16.780
Which is why
I brought my mirror.

20:16.780 --> 20:20.019
You see, I was practicing
the other day...

20:20.019 --> 20:21.550
No, no.
[laughter]

20:21.550 --> 20:23.719
I was practicing the other day
and a thought occurred to me.

20:23.719 --> 20:27.350
You see, I know
mirrors reflect images, light.

20:27.350 --> 20:29.650
But what if one day,
somehow,

20:29.650 --> 20:31.350
it absorbed it instead?

20:31.350 --> 20:32.550
Like a black hole.

20:32.550 --> 20:33.979
What would that look like?

20:33.979 --> 20:35.350
And what would my hand
look like?

20:35.350 --> 20:36.620
Let's find out.

20:36.620 --> 20:38.449
Now, without causing any risk,
injury to myself,

20:38.449 --> 20:42.019
or to any of you,
let's use, uh, playing cards,

20:42.019 --> 20:44.280
because playing cards
have 52 different images.

20:44.280 --> 20:46.120
Which one to choose...?

20:46.120 --> 20:47.350
You know what?
Let's make this simple.

20:47.350 --> 20:48.749
Uh, Penn.
- Yes.

20:48.749 --> 20:50.179
- You can help me select
a card here.

20:50.179 --> 20:51.179
I'm just gonna
flip through here,

20:51.179 --> 20:52.580
just tell me when to stop.

20:52.580 --> 20:54.620
- Stop.
- Stopped me right here.

20:54.620 --> 20:57.919
Now, the idea is that
the mirror is going to absorb

20:57.919 --> 20:59.820
the image of this card.

20:59.820 --> 21:01.719
Eight of clubs.

21:01.719 --> 21:04.120
I'll be fair--
I'll leave it right here.

21:04.120 --> 21:07.850
Now remember, the card
is not going inside the mirror.

21:07.850 --> 21:11.580
No, it's--the mirror is going
to steal the image

21:11.580 --> 21:12.979
like a black hole.

21:12.979 --> 21:14.580
Watch.
[gasps]

21:14.580 --> 21:16.550
Think I felt something.
Look.

21:16.550 --> 21:18.580
<i>[mysterious music playing]</i>

21:18.580 --> 21:21.150
The card
has definitely changed.

21:21.150 --> 21:23.979
And when I mean
that image is gone...

21:23.979 --> 21:26.550
I mean it is completely...

21:26.550 --> 21:28.650
gone.

21:28.650 --> 21:31.650
[applause]

21:31.650 --> 21:34.979
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:34.979 --> 21:37.050
So the big question is:
Why can't you see that image

21:37.050 --> 21:38.719
inside the mirror?

21:38.719 --> 21:40.479
Well, you're not gonna see it
with your human eye,

21:40.479 --> 21:42.120
but there's something
that can help you see it

21:42.120 --> 21:44.050
even if it's
in another dimension--

21:44.050 --> 21:46.150
and I keep it
in this dark box, here,

21:46.150 --> 21:48.150
away from the light--

21:48.150 --> 21:49.350
and that's camera film.

21:49.350 --> 21:50.719
Remember camera film?

21:50.719 --> 21:52.249
All the millennials are like,
"What's that?"

21:52.249 --> 21:53.320
[laughter]

21:53.320 --> 21:54.620
'Cause it's all digital.

21:54.620 --> 21:56.380
But in fact,
they still use camera film

21:56.380 --> 21:58.620
to capture many
paranormal activity.

21:58.620 --> 22:00.080
So watch what happens

22:00.080 --> 22:02.419
when I pass a piece of film
in front of a mirror

22:02.419 --> 22:04.550
that has an image stolen
from another dimension.

22:04.550 --> 22:05.880
I should warn you,

22:05.880 --> 22:08.080
this'll be the strangest thing
you see all night.

22:08.080 --> 22:09.550
Watch.

22:09.550 --> 22:11.880
Eight of clubs.

22:11.880 --> 22:14.449
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:14.449 --> 22:16.419
[audience exclaims]

22:16.419 --> 22:19.419
[applause]

22:19.419 --> 22:22.780
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:22.780 --> 22:24.080
What?

22:24.080 --> 22:26.249
[laughter]

22:26.249 --> 22:30.419
I mean, it's almost like--
like a vampire effect.

22:30.419 --> 22:32.719
And look, if I bring it
right to the surface,

22:32.719 --> 22:36.219
I can actually bring that image
back to this world.

22:36.219 --> 22:38.949
[cheering and applause]

22:38.949 --> 22:42.919
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:42.919 --> 22:44.380
And the image,
it's not even solid--

22:44.380 --> 22:46.979
Look, it's ghostly.

22:46.979 --> 22:48.380
Because it is an essence.

22:48.380 --> 22:49.880
It doesn't belong
to the film,

22:49.880 --> 22:51.519
it belongs
to the playing card

22:51.519 --> 22:53.050
that it came from.

22:53.050 --> 22:54.919
See how that fits both sides?

22:54.919 --> 22:57.780
That film will return
that image.

22:57.780 --> 22:59.719
Home, sweet home.

22:59.719 --> 23:01.800
[cheering and applause]

23:01.819 --> 23:04.619
- Migz!

23:04.619 --> 23:06.079
Whoo!

23:06.079 --> 23:07.550
[cheering and applause]

23:07.550 --> 23:09.379
That was really cool.
- [laughs]

23:09.379 --> 23:10.649
- Did you come up
with that trick?

23:10.649 --> 23:12.480
- Actually, I did.
Funny, of all places,

23:12.480 --> 23:14.250
I came up with the idea
in the shower.

23:14.250 --> 23:15.919
- Oh.
[laughter]

23:15.919 --> 23:17.180
Is that where most
of your ideas come to you?

23:17.180 --> 23:18.450
- A lot of them.
I think some people

23:18.450 --> 23:21.220
sing in the shower,
and I--that just came up.

23:21.220 --> 23:23.220
- Yeah.
- I went to my bathroom mirror

23:23.220 --> 23:25.720
and I just started thinking,
I started staring into it.

23:25.720 --> 23:28.419
- So what do you love most
about magic?

23:28.419 --> 23:30.280
- You know,
there's an engineering aspect.

23:30.280 --> 23:32.419
You know, before I went
into magic--

23:32.419 --> 23:34.579
in high school, I thought I was
gonna go into engineering.

23:34.579 --> 23:36.450
And, you know,
my oldest brother,

23:36.450 --> 23:37.849
he--he became an engineer,

23:37.849 --> 23:40.480
but he and I would go
to the magic shops together.

23:40.480 --> 23:42.020
And, uh, so he became
an engineer,

23:42.020 --> 23:43.450
I became a magician.
[laughter]

23:43.450 --> 23:44.849
But I have
the engineering spirit.

23:44.849 --> 23:47.220
You know again, how do you get
an image inside a mirror?

23:47.220 --> 23:48.919
How do you get something
to appear?

23:48.919 --> 23:51.480
I had to think about all that,
I had to...

23:51.480 --> 23:53.349
in a way, reverse engineer it.

23:53.349 --> 23:55.319
- Yeah.
- You know, you know what you want,

23:55.319 --> 23:57.520
but then you have to figure out
how to do it.

23:57.520 --> 23:59.649
And make it look like magic.

23:59.649 --> 24:01.919
- Yeah.
- That's--that's the hard part.

24:01.919 --> 24:03.680
- All right, let's see
what the boys thought

24:03.680 --> 24:05.180
of your trick.
- Oh, okay.

24:05.180 --> 24:06.649
- Migz, you know,

24:06.649 --> 24:09.649
mirrors automatically...
are magical.

24:09.649 --> 24:11.079
- Yes.
- Whether you're talking

24:11.079 --> 24:12.780
about "Alice In Wonderland:
Through the Looking-Glass"

24:12.780 --> 24:14.520
"Mirror, mirror, on the wall,"
they're just magical objects.

24:14.520 --> 24:17.579
And everybody's always trying
to get them into magic,

24:17.579 --> 24:19.050
and it's really hard to do.

24:19.050 --> 24:21.379
And the mirror
is the centerpiece

24:21.379 --> 24:22.720
of the whole routine.

24:22.720 --> 24:25.849
And yet, the mirror
is just a mirror.

24:25.849 --> 24:27.079
- [chuckles]
- The mirror is,

24:27.079 --> 24:28.379
in a certain sense,
a misdirection

24:28.379 --> 24:31.319
to the other stuff with uh--
with other things.

24:31.319 --> 24:33.919
But I would just say,
for magic words,

24:33.919 --> 24:36.450
some people would say,
"Abracadabra."

24:36.450 --> 24:39.050
We would say...
Ton Onosaka

24:39.050 --> 24:41.480
- [laughing]

24:41.480 --> 24:42.780
- Do you know what that means?
- Hai.

24:42.780 --> 24:44.680
